#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:1
msgid "WebAssembly support"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.14](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.14-brightgreen.svg) for `emscripten`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:5
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: nightly](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-nightly-red.svg) for `wasm32-unknown-unknown`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:7
msgid ""
"Rust has gained support for [WebAssembly](https://webassembly.org/), meaning "
"that you can run Rust code in your browser, client-side."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:10
msgid ""
"In Rust 1.14, we gained support through [emscripten](http://kripken.github."
"io/emscripten-site/index.html). With it installed, you can write Rust code "
"and have it produce [asm.js](http://asmjs.org/) (the precusor to wasm) and/"
"or WebAssembly."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:15
msgid "Here's an example of using this support:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:17
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"$ rustup target add wasm32-unknown-emscripten\n"
"$ echo 'fn main() { println!(\"Hello, Emscripten!\"); }' > hello.rs\n"
"$ rustc --target=wasm32-unknown-emscripten hello.rs\n"
"$ node hello.js\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/webassembly-support.md:24
msgid ""
"However, in the meantime, Rust has also grown its own support, independent "
"from Emscripten. This is known as \"the unknown target\", because instead of "
"`wasm32-unknown-emscripten`, it's `wasm32-unknown-unknown`. This will be the "
"preferred target to use once it's ready, but for now, it's really only well-"
"supported in nightly."
msgstr ""
